n Mindanao against the apparent lack of willingness of Manila to come to terms with the root causes as well as the infusion of arms and ideology from outside. ∑ Zakaria Haji Ahmad and Suzaina Kadir analyse Malaysia’s relatively successful handling of an ethnically divided society, which has permitted impressive stability since 1969. ∑ Chayan Vaddhanaphuti focuses on the non-Thai border peoples of northern Thailand, noting the legacy of the government’s policy of selective citizenship. Ethnic Conflicts in Southeast Asia will be an invaluable resource for scholars of contemporary Southeast Asia as well as in other regions, policy-makers and others, who wish to assess and develop strategies to prevent, modulate and resolve such conflicts.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aConflict managementzSoutheast Asia. 0aEthnic conflictzSoutheast Asia. 0aSocial conflictzSoutheast Asia. 7aSOCIAL SCIENCE / Ethnic Studies / General.2bisacsh1 aAhmad, Zakaria Haji, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrer, Miriam Coronel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKadir, Suzaina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSnitwongse, Kusuma, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aSukma, Rizal, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThan, Tin Maung Maung, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aThompson, W. Scott, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut1 aThompson, W. Scott, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aVaddhanaphuti, Chayan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Backlist (2000-2014) eBook Packagez978311064977208iTi